1
00:00:21,755 --> 00:00:25,987
So you guys all know the story
of Camp Crystal Lake, right?

2
00:00:26,226 --> 00:00:28,751
I mean, come on, surely you
have to know about the legend.

3
00:00:29,195 --> 00:00:30,492
All right, well listen.

4
00:00:30,730 --> 00:00:34,029
I don't want to scare anyone...

5
00:00:34,267 --> 00:00:37,725
but I'm gonna give it to you
straight about Jason.

6
00:00:38,171 --> 00:00:40,298
It all happened
at Camp Crystal Lake...

7
00:00:40,540 --> 00:00:43,668
Camp Blood.

8
00:00:44,110 --> 00:00:48,604
And Jason...was just
a little boy at the time.

9
00:00:49,049 --> 00:00:52,143
He drowned one night.

10
00:00:52,385 --> 00:00:55,286
His mom, who worked
at the camp...

11
00:00:55,522 --> 00:00:57,786
she blamed all the counselors.

12
00:00:58,224 --> 00:01:00,715
Said it was their fault.

13
00:01:01,161 --> 00:01:04,358
She decided to kill
each and every one of them.

14
00:01:04,597 --> 00:01:07,623
Well, legend has it
that Jason didn't drown.

15
00:01:08,068 --> 00:01:10,195
He survived.

16
00:01:10,437 --> 00:01:13,770
And he watched his mother
get beheaded that night.

17
00:01:14,207 --> 00:01:16,505
He took his revenge.

18
00:01:16,743 --> 00:01:21,442
Every year, on Friday the 1 3th,

19
00:01:21,681 --> 00:01:25,742
Jason would just keep
coming back.

20
00:01:26,186 --> 00:01:29,349
Now if you listen
to the old timers in town,

21
00:01:29,589 --> 00:01:32,752
they say that Jason's
still out there,

22
00:01:33,193 --> 00:01:37,129
Which means the Voorhees Curse
is alive and well.

23
00:01:37,363 --> 00:01:41,424
Friday the 13th is his day.

24
00:01:41,668 --> 00:01:44,136
And Camp Crystal Lake...

25
00:01:44,370 --> 00:02:54,172
is his domain.

26
00:02:54,407 --> 00:02:58,241
We had this tiny little movie
that cost $500,000,

27
00:02:58,478 --> 00:03:01,504
which to date has grossed
just under a billion dollars.

28
00:03:01,748 --> 00:03:05,343
It's just an amazing phenomenon.

29
00:03:05,585 --> 00:03:08,486
And not only were we shocked
and surprised and pleased,

30
00:03:08,721 --> 00:03:12,452
but amazed that we even
finished the film.

31
00:03:12,692 --> 00:03:15,252
I hear from people
all over the world,

32
00:03:15,495 --> 00:03:19,329
and I don't quite understand
what the wonderful,

33
00:03:19,566 --> 00:03:23,332
captivating thing is
about this particular film.

34
00:03:23,570 --> 00:03:25,800
I never dreamed when
I was doing the film then

35
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:27,729
the effect it would have
on so many people.

36
00:03:27,974 --> 00:03:29,771
There's actually a lot
of thought

37
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:32,940
and a lot of real talent
that goes into these pictures.

38
00:03:33,379 --> 00:03:36,212
"Friday the 1 3th"
was one of the innovators,

39
00:03:36,449 --> 00:03:38,474
I would say,
of this slasher movie

40
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:40,743
but where the characters
all represented people

41
00:03:40,987 --> 00:03:43,956
that each one of us knew.

42
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:46,358
The best horror
movies find a way

43
00:03:46,593 --> 00:03:48,652
to tap into something
that's truly human.

44
00:03:48,895 --> 00:03:52,296
And there is something so
compelling about the genre

45
00:03:52,532 --> 00:03:55,626
that people will always
come back to it.

46
00:03:55,868 --> 00:03:58,336
I think that the goal is about
scaring the audience

47
00:03:58,571 --> 00:04:00,232
and fear and vulnerability.

48
00:04:00,473 --> 00:04:02,703
We don't know why but
it's something in us

49
00:04:02,942 --> 00:04:04,273
that likes to be scared.

50
00:04:04,510 --> 00:04:05,977
I don't watch the movie,

51
00:04:06,412 --> 00:04:08,778
I pick somebody out
in the audience,

52
00:04:09,015 --> 00:04:11,745
and then watch the evolution
of their heart attack.

53
00:04:11,985 --> 00:04:13,782
It's not rocket science.
It's fun. It's exciting.

54
00:04:14,020 --> 00:04:16,284
The fans so adore
this character.

55
00:04:16,522 --> 00:04:18,513
They like Jason more
than they like the survivors.

56
00:04:18,758 --> 00:04:20,851
They sort of
brought a life to it,

57
00:04:21,294 --> 00:04:23,421
that it would have never had
without 'em.

58
00:04:23,663 --> 00:04:25,858
That's where the power lies
is Jason never dies

59
00:04:26,299 --> 00:04:27,891
because the audience
brings him back to life,

60
00:04:28,334 --> 00:04:31,360
the devoted fans of Jason.

61
00:04:31,604 --> 00:04:33,731
It's a great character to watch
and see what he'll do next.

62
00:04:33,973 --> 00:04:37,568
I don't think it'll really ever
come to a complete end.

63
00:04:37,810 --> 00:04:40,802
A lot of us relate to Jason
because Jason is the outcast.

64
00:04:41,047 --> 00:04:42,981
Like in school, either you're
too tall, you're too short,

65
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:44,940
you're too heavy,
you have buck teeth,

66
00:04:45,385 --> 00:04:48,252
you speak with a lisp,
we all tie in somehow,

67
00:04:48,488 --> 00:04:50,388
going, 'Oh, I understand that,
I was the different kid.'

68
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:52,022
It's just a basic part
of the human struggle.

69
00:04:52,458 --> 00:04:54,255
Jason represents that force that
you're going to come up against.

70
00:04:54,494 --> 00:04:56,428
You know, we all want to be
that person

71
00:04:56,663 --> 00:04:58,961
that feels like we can,
you know, stop evil

72
00:04:59,399 --> 00:05:01,367
and save the person
that we love.

73
00:05:01,601 --> 00:05:03,535
I think that we need
these monsters, these bogeymen,

74
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:06,568
these characters who embody
all evil

75
00:05:06,806 --> 00:05:08,933
because we can't deal
with the real evil

76
00:05:09,375 --> 00:05:11,502
that we have to
in our day to day lives.

77
00:05:11,744 --> 00:05:14,042
If you can take that darkness
out and look at it,

78
00:05:14,480 --> 00:05:15,708
then you can conquer it,
you can defeat it,

79
00:05:15,948 --> 00:05:17,472
you can actually deal with it.

80
00:05:17,717 --> 00:05:18,775
It's when we try and hide it
from the light

81
00:05:19,018 --> 00:05:36,357
that it overcomes us.

82
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:38,297
In the early 1 970's,

83
00:05:38,538 --> 00:05:40,904
Connecticut-based filmmaker
Sean S. Cunningham

84
00:05:41,341 --> 00:05:42,638
was struggling to make
a name for himself,

85
00:05:42,875 --> 00:05:44,467
scraping by on a diet

86
00:05:44,711 --> 00:05:46,303
of industrial shorts
and commercials

87
00:05:46,546 --> 00:05:49,310
and even the occasional
soft-core porn.

88
00:05:49,549 --> 00:05:50,948
Back in the early 70's,
a big change was happening

89
00:05:51,384 --> 00:05:52,851
in the movie business.

90
00:05:53,086 --> 00:05:54,815
There had been success
with documentary forms

91
00:05:55,054 --> 00:05:57,352
and with hand-held cameras.

92
00:05:57,590 --> 00:06:01,082
And there was a sense of
anything was possible.

93
00:06:01,527 --> 00:06:03,995
You know, just grab your camera,
grab your equipment,

94
00:06:04,430 --> 00:06:05,556
get in the back of the station
wagon and go shoot it.

95
00:06:05,798 --> 00:06:06,696
You can compete
with the big guys.

96
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:08,833
He was making little movies.

97
00:06:09,068 --> 00:06:10,865
There was a film he made
called "Together,"

98
00:06:11,104 --> 00:06:12,833
and it starred Marilyn Chambers

99
00:06:13,072 --> 00:06:14,039
who went to the local
high school.

100
00:06:14,474 --> 00:06:16,999
It was a marital aid film

101
00:06:17,443 --> 00:06:20,503
for couples who were trying to
strengthen their marital bond,

102
00:06:20,747 --> 00:06:22,738
as it would be, in the bedroom.

103
00:06:22,982 --> 00:06:25,576
We had a mutual friend.
His name was Bud Talbot,

104
00:06:25,818 --> 00:06:27,786
who I was working with
on a film.

105
00:06:28,020 --> 00:06:29,681
I think he helped Sean raise
some of the money,

106
00:06:29,922 --> 00:06:32,789
and uh, this movie, "Case of the
Full Moon Murders,"

107
00:06:33,025 --> 00:06:34,890
and it starred Harry Reams.
It was very soft.

108
00:06:35,128 --> 00:06:37,062
In the softcore world.

109
00:06:37,497 --> 00:06:40,432
7:35 a. m.
We were shown to a bedroom.

110
00:06:40,666 --> 00:06:42,395
A male corpse
with an enormous erection

111
00:06:42,635 --> 00:06:43,897
was covered with a blanket.

112
00:06:44,137 --> 00:06:46,537
Our suspicions
were immediately aroused.

113
00:06:46,773 --> 00:06:48,138
In the mid-seventies,
everybody said we need

114
00:06:48,574 --> 00:06:50,405
nice, clean, wholesome films.

115
00:06:50,643 --> 00:06:52,543
So we did two very nice, clean,
wholesome films.

116
00:06:52,779 --> 00:06:56,442
And they made absolutely
zero dollars.

117
00:06:56,682 --> 00:06:59,515
And now I had to get
another job.

118
00:06:59,752 --> 00:07:01,686
Somehow or other I had to get
something going.

119
00:07:01,921 --> 00:07:06,153
That something turned out to be
1 972's "Last House On the Left."

120
00:07:06,592 --> 00:07:08,992
To avoid fainting,
keep repeating:

121
00:07:09,429 --> 00:07:12,557
"It's only a movie.
Only a movie..."

122
00:07:12,799 --> 00:07:14,494
The film
produced by Cunningham,

123
00:07:14,734 --> 00:07:16,599
and directed by Wes Craven,

124
00:07:16,836 --> 00:07:18,770
who would go on to create 1 984's
"A Nightmare On Elm Street,"

125
00:07:19,005 --> 00:07:21,030
presented a brutal portrait

126
00:07:21,474 --> 00:07:24,671
of violence and visceral horror
in small-town America.

127
00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:29,405
Well, we were co-producers
of "Last House on the Left,"

128
00:07:29,649 --> 00:07:31,674
which I think was
a very important horror film.

129
00:07:31,918 --> 00:07:34,512
And it's still playing today
all over the world.

130
00:07:34,754 --> 00:07:36,187
Although none of
Sean Cunningham's early efforts

131
00:07:36,622 --> 00:07:38,146
achieved mainstream success,

132
00:07:38,591 --> 00:07:42,118
his next brainchild,
with a considerable debt

133
00:07:42,562 --> 00:07:46,089
owed to John Carpenter's 1 978
screen shocker "Halloween,"

134
00:07:46,532 --> 00:07:49,558
would launch a whole new
sub-genre of horror.

135
00:07:49,802 --> 00:07:52,896
I had thought of this title
some time ago

136
00:07:53,139 --> 00:07:54,163
called Friday the 1 3th.
And I said to myself,

137
00:07:54,607 --> 00:07:57,098
'lf I had a film called
Friday the 1 3th,

138
00:07:57,543 --> 00:07:58,942
I could sell that.

139
00:07:59,178 --> 00:08:00,975
And Sean called me up and said,

140
00:08:01,214 --> 00:08:03,444
"Halloween" is making incredible
money at the box office,

141
00:08:03,683 --> 00:08:04,547
Iet's rip it off."

142
00:08:04,784 --> 00:08:06,877
That is keeping it real.

143
00:08:07,119 --> 00:08:08,051
And I said,
"Here's what we're gonna do.

144
00:08:08,488 --> 00:08:10,115
We're gonna take out an ad
in Variety,

145
00:08:10,556 --> 00:08:12,786
and put at the top 'From the
people who brought you

146
00:08:13,025 --> 00:08:15,994
"Last House on the Left"

147
00:08:16,229 --> 00:08:18,697
comes the most terrifying
film ever made.

148
00:08:18,931 --> 00:08:20,558
"Friday the 1 3th."

149
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,529
And that's all we had.

150
00:08:22,768 --> 00:08:23,894
We really didn't know what we
were going to make.

151
00:08:24,136 --> 00:08:24,192
We just wanted to see if anybody
would be interested

152
00:08:24,637 --> 00:08:26,901
in buying it.

153
00:08:27,139 --> 00:08:28,800
Cunningham was able
to secure financing

154
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:30,941
for "Friday the 1 3th"
through the same trio

155
00:08:31,177 --> 00:08:32,235
of east coast investors

156
00:08:32,678 --> 00:08:33,872
who funded and distributed

157
00:08:34,113 --> 00:08:36,240
"Last House on the Left."

158
00:08:36,682 --> 00:08:39,742
Robert Barsamian, Stephen
Minasian, and Philip Scuderi,

159
00:08:39,986 --> 00:08:42,716
owners of
the Esquire Theaters chain,

160
00:08:42,955 --> 00:08:45,685
and who, under their Georgetown
Productions banner,

161
00:08:45,925 --> 00:08:48,519
were ready to make their mark
on motion picture history.

162
00:08:48,761 --> 00:08:52,663
But first, they needed
one thing: a script.

163
00:08:52,899 --> 00:08:54,696
The longest part
of the process

164
00:08:54,934 --> 00:08:56,561
of creating the first
"Friday the 1 3th"

165
00:08:56,802 --> 00:08:58,736
was figuring out the venue.

166
00:08:58,971 --> 00:09:01,769
So I had to find some territory

167
00:09:02,008 --> 00:09:04,101
that was adult-free,
more-or-less.

168
00:09:04,544 --> 00:09:06,068
Camp Crystal Lake is jinxed!

169
00:09:06,312 --> 00:09:08,803
Oh, terrific.

170
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:10,743
So we came up with summer camp,
Sean said, "let's go with it,"

171
00:09:10,983 --> 00:09:12,280
and that was that.

172
00:09:12,718 --> 00:09:13,946
The thing about the story
in "Friday the 1 3th,"

173
00:09:14,186 --> 00:09:17,622
is that it's so
profoundly simple.

174
00:09:17,857 --> 00:09:19,518
I think part of that
had to do with the fact

175
00:09:19,759 --> 00:09:22,091
that we had very little time
to waste

176
00:09:22,328 --> 00:09:25,126
on conventional things
like character and plot.

177
00:09:25,565 --> 00:09:28,625
We had this notion
that these kids

178
00:09:28,868 --> 00:09:30,301
would be out at a summer camp,

179
00:09:30,736 --> 00:09:33,261
and would be threatened by some
kind of serial killer,

180
00:09:33,706 --> 00:09:36,174
and we would then be surprised
to discover

181
00:09:36,609 --> 00:09:37,701
who the serial killer was
at the end.

182
00:09:37,944 --> 00:09:39,775
Who are you!?.

183
00:09:40,012 --> 00:09:41,843
I thought that basically
what I had done

184
00:09:42,081 --> 00:09:45,278
was I had taken
mom and apple pie,

185
00:09:45,718 --> 00:09:49,882
and the clean, wonderful, let's
have a ball Pepsi generation,

186
00:09:50,122 --> 00:09:51,919
these clean cut kids who are out
having fun

187
00:09:52,158 --> 00:09:53,785
and unfettered
by adult restrictions,

188
00:09:54,026 --> 00:09:55,288
and stood it on its head.

189
00:09:55,728 --> 00:09:57,696
And I just knocked them off
one-by-one.

190
00:09:57,930 --> 00:10:00,899
By the fall of 1 979,
with a script in hand

191
00:10:01,133 --> 00:10:04,933
and a production budget of
approximately $550,000,

192
00:10:05,171 --> 00:10:07,696
Cunningham and his protÈgÈ
Steve Miner

193
00:10:07,940 --> 00:10:10,306
began searching
for the ideal location

194
00:10:10,743 --> 00:10:14,110
that would become the cursed
hamlet of Crystal Lake.

195
00:10:14,347 --> 00:10:16,747
The film was shot in a small
little Boy Scout camp

196
00:10:16,983 --> 00:10:19,213
called 'Camp No-be-Bo-Sco.'

197
00:10:19,652 --> 00:10:21,119
It was off-season so all
the kids had gone home,

198
00:10:21,354 --> 00:10:23,219
and we were able
to take it over.

199
00:10:23,656 --> 00:10:26,284
So it was a standing,
working camp.

200
00:10:26,726 --> 00:10:29,991
And, it was a whole bunch of
log cabins and all that stuff.

201
00:10:30,229 --> 00:10:32,060
It was an archery range, it was
a lake, it was everything.

202
00:10:32,298 --> 00:10:34,163
It was just a little bit colder

203
00:10:34,400 --> 00:10:35,799
than it normally would be
in the summer.

204
00:10:36,035 --> 00:10:37,832
Like most tales set at
summer camp,

205
00:10:38,070 --> 00:10:40,129
"Friday the 1 3th" begins around
a campfire.

206
00:10:40,373 --> 00:10:43,900
It's Friday, June 1 3, 1 958,

207
00:10:44,143 --> 00:10:46,771
and lovelorn counselors
Claudette and Barry

208
00:10:47,013 --> 00:10:49,038
soon find their late-night tryst
interrupted

209
00:10:49,281 --> 00:10:51,181
by a murderous stranger,

210
00:10:51,417 --> 00:10:53,783
making them the first
on-screen victims

211
00:10:54,020 --> 00:10:55,351
in what would become
one of the biggest body counts

212
00:10:55,788 --> 00:10:58,018
in film history.

213
00:10:58,257 --> 00:11:01,124
Fans have often asked
if we planned to shoot

214
00:11:01,360 --> 00:11:03,954
a more gruesome on-screen death
for the character of Claudette.

215
00:11:04,196 --> 00:11:06,027
There are even photos that show
her throat being sliced open

216
00:11:06,265 --> 00:11:08,733
by a machete.

217
00:11:08,968 --> 00:11:10,629
I think it was Savini, you know,

218
00:11:10,870 --> 00:11:11,859
fooling around
in the makeup room,

219
00:11:12,104 --> 00:11:14,834
because we didn't have time
to shoot

220
00:11:15,074 --> 00:11:17,133
that kind of a big production,

221
00:11:17,376 --> 00:11:19,674
As I originally laid out the
character of the killer,

222
00:11:19,912 --> 00:11:22,346
and the clues as to who
the killer was,

223
00:11:22,782 --> 00:11:25,376
in the original scene,
you saw a missing finger.

224
00:11:25,818 --> 00:11:30,050
And so that every time you saw
this hand without a finger,

225
00:11:30,289 --> 00:11:31,347
that would be your clue
that this was the killer.

226
00:11:31,791 --> 00:11:33,691
And for time
and budgetary constraints,

227
00:11:33,926 --> 00:11:35,291
that got dropped out.

228
00:11:35,728 --> 00:11:37,355
As the film shifts
to present day,

229
00:11:37,797 --> 00:11:40,027
we are introduced to a cast
of fresh faces

230
00:11:40,266 --> 00:11:42,291
culled from New York's
thriving theater scene.

231
00:11:42,735 --> 00:11:45,203
And as would become the rule for
all future Fridays,

232
00:11:45,438 --> 00:11:47,406
the young, would-be victims
had to be likable,

233
00:11:47,840 --> 00:11:49,865
and they had to work cheap.

234
00:11:50,109 --> 00:11:52,805
My partner at the time,
Julie Hughes and l,

235
00:11:53,045 --> 00:11:55,980
were pretty much the major
casting people on Broadway.

236
00:11:56,215 --> 00:11:58,183
But we had done a few films.

237
00:11:58,417 --> 00:12:01,215
So we looked forward
to doing this,

238
00:12:01,454 --> 00:12:05,151
particularly with the idea of
finding all sorts of new talent

239
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:07,916
for the young kids in the film.

240
00:12:08,160 --> 00:12:10,958
Julie Hughes had said, 'You
know, you're not right for this,

241
00:12:11,197 --> 00:12:14,132
but they're doing this movie,
and they need camp counselors,

242
00:12:14,366 --> 00:12:15,765
and you would be perfect.'

243
00:12:16,001 --> 00:12:18,026
So then they sent me
to meet Sean

244
00:12:18,270 --> 00:12:19,794
and audition for
"Friday the 1 3th."

