729
00:33:57,335 --> 00:33:58,734
to the girl
who went out for lunch,

730
00:33:59,170 --> 00:34:02,037
claimed to have
written this scene (laughs).

731
00:34:02,273 --> 00:34:03,433
But, I wrote it.

732
00:34:03,674 --> 00:34:05,574
At first, they were thinking

733
00:34:05,810 --> 00:34:09,610
of having Noel Cunningham,
Sean's son, do it.

734
00:34:10,048 --> 00:34:12,278
But his wife
would have none of that.

735
00:34:12,517 --> 00:34:14,542
My mother said,
'You're out of your mind

736
00:34:14,786 --> 00:34:17,220
if I'm going to let my kid
spend four hours in a lake

737
00:34:17,455 --> 00:34:18,786
in the middle of fall
in New Jersey

738
00:34:19,223 --> 00:34:21,214
to be in your stupid movie.

739
00:34:21,459 --> 00:34:24,019
Were it not for her,
I would have been Jason.

740
00:34:24,262 --> 00:34:26,526
I would have been
the first Jason.

741
00:34:26,764 --> 00:34:31,360
And I'm not bitter

742
00:34:31,602 --> 00:34:33,763
Prior to that I had been
in "Manny's Orphans,"

743
00:34:34,205 --> 00:34:36,730
and I played this kid Roger,

744
00:34:37,175 --> 00:34:40,372
who was like a slightly
sex-obsessed little kid.

745
00:34:40,611 --> 00:34:43,409
So Steve Miner
just kind of said,

746
00:34:43,648 --> 00:34:44,546
'Hey, let's get Ari to do it.'

747
00:34:44,782 --> 00:34:46,511
My investors in Boston

748
00:34:46,751 --> 00:34:49,185
wanted to have it more
extreme and seaweed,

749
00:34:49,420 --> 00:34:51,684
and maybe he could be deformed
a little bit,

750
00:34:52,123 --> 00:34:55,058
and Tom Savini said,
'Oh, I've got a great idea.'

751
00:34:55,293 --> 00:34:56,624
And he started to make his head
lopsided

752
00:34:56,861 --> 00:34:59,193
and put a weird eye on him.

753
00:34:59,430 --> 00:35:01,091
And it just became
more and more extreme.

754
00:35:01,332 --> 00:35:05,598
We dredged up
part of the pond

755
00:35:05,837 --> 00:35:09,671
and Tom Savini
used real swamp muck for that.

756
00:35:10,108 --> 00:35:12,269
I came upon a picture
in this group of Polaroids

757
00:35:12,510 --> 00:35:14,375
and I said, 'And who's this??'

758
00:35:14,612 --> 00:35:18,104
And he said,
'Oh, that's your son.'

759
00:35:18,349 --> 00:35:20,613
And I said, 'Well, why does he
look so strange?. '

760
00:35:20,852 --> 00:35:24,151
And he said, 'Well, he said,
he's a mongoloid.

761
00:35:24,388 --> 00:35:27,357
I said, 'He's what?.!'

762
00:35:27,592 --> 00:35:29,856
I said, that wasn't
in the script!'

763
00:35:30,294 --> 00:35:32,694
That's a nightmare Jason
that comes out of the water.

764
00:35:33,131 --> 00:35:37,261
The real Jason was probably just
an almost ordinary child.

765
00:35:37,502 --> 00:35:40,835
And so that part
is a total dream,

766
00:35:41,272 --> 00:35:42,705
or it was in my mind.

767
00:35:43,141 --> 00:35:45,735
We wind up having this gorgeous,
idyllic setting.

768
00:35:46,177 --> 00:35:48,645
You know, on the lake,
in the canoe.

769
00:35:48,880 --> 00:35:51,713
I did everything I could
to tell the audience

770
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:55,779
that it's okay now.
You can relax. It's over.

771
00:35:56,220 --> 00:35:59,314
But the strongest aspect is
Harry Manfredini's soundtrack.

772
00:35:59,557 --> 00:36:02,390
That was really the first
time in the film

773
00:36:02,627 --> 00:36:05,790
where the music stopped being
the music for the killer

774
00:36:06,230 --> 00:36:12,191
and started to really
manipulate you.

775
00:36:12,436 --> 00:36:15,132
It's over. The police have come.
The cavalry's here.

776
00:36:15,373 --> 00:36:18,206
It went on so long
that even the people

777
00:36:18,442 --> 00:36:20,603
who were positive something
was going to happen

778
00:36:20,845 --> 00:36:22,836
pretty much gave up that
something was going to happen.

779
00:36:23,281 --> 00:36:25,613
Alice has this look of hope.

780
00:36:25,850 --> 00:36:26,748
And she's just trailing her
fingers in the water.

781
00:36:27,185 --> 00:36:31,349
And BAM!

782
00:36:31,589 --> 00:36:33,853
And it was a wonderful addition.

783
00:36:34,292 --> 00:36:35,759
I mean I think
that Sean's idea is right.

784
00:36:36,194 --> 00:36:38,355
That it really wasn't finished
until that.

785
00:36:38,596 --> 00:36:40,621
One of the really delightful
things that we could do

786
00:36:40,865 --> 00:36:43,561
is go to a screening and watch
the people jump at the end,

787
00:36:43,801 --> 00:36:47,362
because for whatever reasons,
this ending got 'em.

788
00:36:47,605 --> 00:36:49,368
I'm telling you, people just
flew out of the seats

789
00:36:49,607 --> 00:36:51,438
and ran out of the theater

790
00:36:51,676 --> 00:36:53,769
and Sean was just like
a little kid going,

791
00:36:54,212 --> 00:36:56,373
'l got 'em, I got 'em all!'

792
00:36:56,614 --> 00:36:58,514
I think without
that single moment,

793
00:36:58,749 --> 00:37:00,182
I don't think Friday would have
been half as successful

794
00:37:00,418 --> 00:37:02,477
as it was.

795
00:37:02,720 --> 00:37:04,745
Because the people got to leave,
strangely enough,

796
00:37:04,989 --> 00:37:06,251
with a smile on their face.

797
00:37:06,490 --> 00:37:08,515
They got tricked,
and they loved it.

798
00:37:08,759 --> 00:37:11,523
And then the next scene
Alice wakes up,

799
00:37:11,762 --> 00:37:14,196
and they tell her
no one else was found.

800
00:37:14,432 --> 00:37:16,957
It was only her.
Everyone else is dead.

801
00:37:17,401 --> 00:37:21,269
I remember the scene
in the hospital vividly

802
00:37:21,505 --> 00:37:23,803
because, when I sort of ask,

803
00:37:24,242 --> 00:37:26,642
when she asks me
about the boy and I go,

804
00:37:26,877 --> 00:37:28,868
Ma'am, we didn't find any boy.

805
00:37:29,313 --> 00:37:31,577
And she says

806
00:37:31,816 --> 00:37:33,443
Then he's still there.

807
00:37:33,684 --> 00:37:36,676
And he certainly was.

808
00:37:36,921 --> 00:37:40,584
I knew that we're looking
at a Part 2 here.

809
00:37:40,825 --> 00:37:43,293
Those little drops at the end,

810
00:37:43,527 --> 00:37:45,392
Those little ripples
in the water at the end.

811
00:37:45,630 --> 00:37:47,495
It's like, well, was it a dream,
wasn't it at dream?.

812
00:37:47,732 --> 00:37:49,290
Were those raindrops,
or were those air bubbles?.

813
00:37:49,533 --> 00:37:52,331
And I think now
we know the answer.

814
00:37:52,570 --> 00:37:55,004
In early 1 980,
the film was picked up

815
00:37:55,439 --> 00:37:58,374
for domestic distribution
by Frank Mancuso, Sr.

816
00:37:58,609 --> 00:38:01,669
VP of Paramount Pictures,
who planned a national release

817
00:38:01,912 --> 00:38:03,880
and a multi-million dollar
marketing campaign.

818
00:38:04,315 --> 00:38:06,783
The risk paid off,
and for Paramount,

819
00:38:07,018 --> 00:38:09,350
Sean Cunningham
and Georgetown Productions,

820
00:38:09,587 --> 00:38:10,679
"Friday the 1 3th"
was about to become

821
00:38:10,921 --> 00:38:13,389
their lucky day.

822
00:38:13,624 --> 00:38:16,821
Frank Mancuso was head
of distribution at Paramount.

823
00:38:17,061 --> 00:38:19,757
And he had the idea
of treating this little movie

824
00:38:19,997 --> 00:38:22,864
as if it were a real movie.

825
00:38:23,301 --> 00:38:26,270
And had no stars,
and nothing recognizable

826
00:38:26,504 --> 00:38:28,972
except this sort of strange,
superstitious title.

827
00:38:29,407 --> 00:38:32,035
And went out
and sold it like crazy.

828
00:38:32,476 --> 00:38:34,910
1

829
00:38:35,346 --> 00:38:38,838
2

830
00:38:39,083 --> 00:38:40,914
3

831
00:38:41,352 --> 00:38:45,413
Friday the 1 3th.
You may only see it once.

832
00:38:45,656 --> 00:38:50,719
But that will be enough.

833
00:38:50,961 --> 00:38:53,953
"Friday the 1 3th"
opened on May 9, 1 980,

834
00:38:54,398 --> 00:38:58,528
eventually taking in $39.7
million at the U.S. box office.

835
00:38:58,769 --> 00:39:00,737
If the reason behind the film's
immense popularity

836
00:39:00,971 --> 00:39:02,598
was lost
on mainstream critics,

837
00:39:02,840 --> 00:39:05,434
who not only hated the film,
but eviscerated it.

838
00:39:05,676 --> 00:39:08,736
no one was more stunned by its
success than its creators.

839
00:39:08,979 --> 00:39:10,913
For better or worse,
"Friday the 1 3th"

840
00:39:11,349 --> 00:39:12,782
would change their lives.

841
00:39:13,017 --> 00:39:16,646
and the horror genre...forever.

842
00:39:16,887 --> 00:39:18,616
When it first started,
it was repeat business

843
00:39:18,856 --> 00:39:19,982
that made it successful.

844
00:39:20,424 --> 00:39:23,587
It was teenage girls
going to see it

845
00:39:23,828 --> 00:39:25,318
and then bringing
their girlfriends,

846
00:39:25,563 --> 00:39:26,996
and then dragging
their boyfriend to see it.

847
00:39:27,431 --> 00:39:28,955
It was all this repeat business.

848
00:39:29,400 --> 00:39:32,028
Before "Friday the 1 3th,"
maybe the most successful

849
00:39:32,470 --> 00:39:33,698
quote-unquote horror movies

850
00:39:33,938 --> 00:39:36,338
were handled on a very
limited basis,

851
00:39:36,574 --> 00:39:38,371
Iike "Halloween"
or even "Carrie."

852
00:39:38,609 --> 00:39:40,941
They weren't treated
as major motion pictures.

853
00:39:41,379 --> 00:39:44,371
The fact that that one
became so wildly successful,

854
00:39:44,615 --> 00:39:46,742
the producers jumped on it
as this is an opportunity

855
00:39:46,984 --> 00:39:49,714
for us to sell this off
and make more and more films.

856
00:39:49,954 --> 00:39:52,616
You also have to remember
this was back in 1 980.

857
00:39:52,857 --> 00:39:55,519
This was before cable TV.
Before the internet.

858
00:39:55,760 --> 00:40:00,595
Before VHS really. Before DVD.

859
00:40:00,831 --> 00:40:04,562
So if you wanted to get anything
that was really titillating,

860
00:40:04,802 --> 00:40:07,566
horror was the only place
you could go.

861
00:40:07,805 --> 00:40:09,898
There was something,
um, exciting about it

862
00:40:10,141 --> 00:40:11,540
'cause it was breaking
new ground.

863
00:40:11,776 --> 00:40:13,607
And of course your parents
didn't want you to see it,

864
00:40:13,844 --> 00:40:16,005
which only made you want to
see it that much more,

865
00:40:16,447 --> 00:40:18,005
and made it that much
better when you did see it.

866
00:40:18,449 --> 00:40:21,612
The modern horror movie
was kind of born,

867
00:40:21,852 --> 00:40:24,980
because it now became
a possible player

868
00:40:25,423 --> 00:40:27,755
in the mainstream distribution
of movies.

869
00:40:27,992 --> 00:40:29,653
It's like "Night of the
Living Dead" with Romero.

870
00:40:29,894 --> 00:40:32,158
Those guys involved in that
all had careers after that.

871
00:40:32,596 --> 00:40:34,791
I thought it was
a piece of crap.

872
00:40:35,032 --> 00:40:38,160
And l, truthfully, didn't care
if my name got on it or not.

873
00:40:38,602 --> 00:40:42,436
At that time. (laughs)
And then when it opened,

874
00:40:42,673 --> 00:40:44,766
(laughs) My god!

875
00:40:45,009 --> 00:40:46,704
The critical reaction
to "Friday the 13th,"

876
00:40:46,944 --> 00:40:50,812
was so abysmal that I knew
we were going to be a success.

877
00:40:51,048 --> 00:40:53,516
I mean, there was one critic
who wanted us all arrested

878
00:40:53,751 --> 00:40:56,117
and tried for horrible crimes
against humanity.

879
00:40:56,554 --> 00:40:58,579
I'm convinced it has
something to do

880
00:40:58,823 --> 00:40:59,790
with the growth of the women's
movement in America

881
00:41:00,024 --> 00:41:01,889
in the last decade.

882
00:41:02,126 --> 00:41:04,788
I think that these films are
some sort of primordial response

883
00:41:05,029 --> 00:41:07,964
by some very sick people,
of men

884
00:41:08,199 --> 00:41:09,757
saying 'get back
in your place, women.'

885
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:14,130
And I was upset by all of
the terrible publicity,

886
00:41:14,572 --> 00:41:17,132
and the scorn
and the ridicule.

887
00:41:17,575 --> 00:41:20,544
Gene Siskel gave us
this scathing review.

888
00:41:20,778 --> 00:41:23,212
I think he even may have
published Betsy Palmer's address

889
00:41:23,647 --> 00:41:25,638
saying, 'write to her
nasty things

890
00:41:25,883 --> 00:41:27,578
because she's a terrible person.

891
00:41:27,818 --> 00:41:31,447
How dare Betsy Palmer
play a role like this

892
00:41:31,689 --> 00:41:33,623
in "Friday the 1 3th,"

893
00:41:33,858 --> 00:41:36,122
when she has made herself
so lovable,

894
00:41:36,560 --> 00:41:38,790
on "I've Got a Secret
all these years,

895
00:41:39,029 --> 00:41:40,929
and all the television shows
she's done.

896
00:41:41,165 --> 00:41:43,725
How dare she play a role
like that,

897
00:41:43,968 --> 00:41:46,960
and insult her viewing audience?.

898
00:41:47,204 --> 00:41:49,798
And I thought, 'Well,
those who can, do,

899
00:41:50,040 --> 00:41:51,132
and those who can't, criticize.'

900
00:41:51,575 --> 00:41:53,042
The first of the slashers

901
00:41:53,277 --> 00:41:57,873
were to reflect the changing
attitudes and ideas

902
00:41:58,115 --> 00:41:59,946
about women
and what they could do.

903
00:42:00,184 --> 00:42:03,153
I think we go back to Jamie Lee
Curtis in "Halloween,"

904
00:42:03,587 --> 00:42:06,055
Sissy Spacek in "Carrie."

905
00:42:06,290 --> 00:42:08,053
Sigourney Weaver.

906
00:42:08,292 --> 00:42:10,920
Alice, all of a sudden,
is the sole survivor.

907
00:42:11,161 --> 00:42:13,925
And I believe it was
a direct reflection

908
00:42:14,164 --> 00:42:16,689
of what was going on
in the world.

909
00:42:16,934 --> 00:42:20,927
And I think "Friday the 1 3th"
really empowered women.

910
00:42:21,171 --> 00:42:23,139
So after "Friday the 1 3th"
was released,

911
00:42:23,574 --> 00:42:26,509
there spawned
a whole new industry

912
00:42:26,744 --> 00:42:30,180
of teenage horror films
based on holidays,

913
00:42:30,614 --> 00:42:32,206
or based on a serial killer,

914
00:42:32,650 --> 00:42:34,515
based on very low budgets
and low writing.

915
00:42:34,752 --> 00:42:39,086
Strangely enough, I think that
people often sort of imitated

916
00:42:39,323 --> 00:42:42,156
my mistakes rather than
the stuff that I got right.

917
00:42:42,593 --> 00:42:44,891
Well, "Friday the 1 3th" was
the greatest experience for me

918
00:42:45,129 --> 00:42:47,996
up until the point
of after it opening.

919
00:42:48,232 --> 00:42:49,961
It was huge. It was fabulous.

920
00:42:50,200 --> 00:42:52,065
It was an actor's dream
come true.

921
00:42:52,303 --> 00:42:53,895
It certainly was for me.

922
00:42:54,138 --> 00:42:58,040
And then, slowly I realized
I had a stalker.

923
00:42:58,275 --> 00:43:01,301
Stalking was not taken seriously
back in 1 980.

924
00:43:01,745 --> 00:43:05,078
And it wasn't,
it wasn't something

925
00:43:05,316 --> 00:43:07,284
that everyone was aware of.

926
00:43:07,718 --> 00:43:10,186
I was starting to get
phone calls back then,

927
00:43:10,621 --> 00:43:11,815
it was so easy
to get phone numbers.

928
00:43:12,056 --> 00:43:13,819
He, he got into my apartment.

929
00:43:14,058 --> 00:43:17,289
For over a year, I didn't know
who my stalker was

930
00:43:17,728 --> 00:43:19,787
and what happened was,
he befriended me,

931
00:43:20,030 --> 00:43:21,998
he actually worked his way
into my life

932
00:43:22,232 --> 00:43:24,132
so I was actually
giving him information

933
00:43:24,368 --> 00:43:26,996
about my stalker.

934
00:43:27,237 --> 00:43:30,138
I had an ordeal with
him up close at one point,

935
00:43:30,374 --> 00:43:32,638
which in itself,
is a horror movie.

936
00:43:32,876 --> 00:43:37,074
Eventually, I had a gun
to my head.

937
00:43:37,314 --> 00:43:42,274
And I was able to talk
the fan down.

938
00:43:42,720 --> 00:43:44,779
It really took its toll
for a while.

939
00:43:45,022 --> 00:43:47,684
But, it's all okay now.
It's all good now.

940
00:43:47,925 --> 00:43:50,291
And having three generations
of fans

941
00:43:50,728 --> 00:43:54,721
from around the world
that fly in to wherever I am,

942
00:43:54,965 --> 00:43:56,159
at a city or a convention,

943
00:43:56,400 --> 00:43:58,766
that really talk to me
and care,

944
00:43:59,003 --> 00:44:00,061
and tell me how much
it affected them

945
00:44:00,304 --> 00:44:01,828
when they found out.

946
00:44:02,072 --> 00:44:04,666
It's just a gift.
It's a beautiful thing.

947
00:44:04,908 --> 00:44:07,376
And, I thank them.

948
00:44:07,811 --> 00:44:10,803
I've turned around
my thinking about it.

949
00:44:11,048 --> 00:44:13,744
I think it worked out just
the way it was supposed to.

950
00:44:13,984 --> 00:44:16,885
And I have never felt
that I damaged my career.

951
00:44:17,121 --> 00:44:20,386
If anything, there are people
that would never know I existed.

952
00:44:20,824 --> 00:44:24,055
We had this tiny little movie
that cost $500,000,

953
00:44:24,294 --> 00:44:26,888
made in a boy scout camp
in New Jersey.

954
00:44:27,131 --> 00:44:31,090
I (laughs) just cannot imagine
how we got here from there.

955
00:44:31,335 --> 00:44:34,668
It kind of launched
the whole mythology.

956
00:44:34,905 --> 00:44:43,180
And it wasn't by accident,
but it was kind of good fortune.

957
00:44:43,180 --> 00:44:56,651
And it wasn't by accident,
but it was kind of good fortune.

958
00:44:56,894 --> 00:44:59,055
By the end of 1 980,
Friday the 1 3th

959
00:44:59,296 --> 00:45:01,161
had already unleashed
a slew of imitators,

960
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:02,956
throwing open
the floodgates

961
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:04,861
for fledgling independent
distributors

962
00:45:05,102 --> 00:45:07,093
and major Hollywood
studios

963
00:45:07,337 --> 00:45:10,363
Iooking to cash in on
the new slasher film craze.

964
00:45:10,808 --> 00:45:13,242
With each film seemingly
made faster,

965
00:45:13,477 --> 00:45:15,445
cheaper and gorier
than the last.

966
00:45:15,879 --> 00:45:18,370
With Paramount Pictures
pushing for a sequel,

967
00:45:18,816 --> 00:45:20,875
Sean S. Cunningham grappled
with the question

968
00:45:21,118 --> 00:45:23,313
of what to do when
virtually the entire cast

969
