03:33:49,082 --> 03:33:51,050
Cinematically, it's one of
the more interesting sequences

5024
03:33:51,285 --> 03:33:52,445
in any of the "Friday" films.

5025
03:33:52,886 --> 03:33:55,980
The scene
where Megan kills Jason

5026
03:33:56,223 --> 03:33:58,316
with the outboard motor was shot
in two different places.

5027
03:33:58,559 --> 03:34:01,027
All of the underwater scenes

5028
03:34:01,261 --> 03:34:02,990
were shot in
a temperature-controlled tank

5029
03:34:03,230 --> 03:34:05,130
in Los Angeles

5030
03:34:05,365 --> 03:34:06,923
well after we'd filmed
the rest of the movie.

5031
03:34:07,167 --> 03:34:08,065
And when I say
they chained me down,

5032
03:34:08,302 --> 03:34:10,065
they did chain me down.

5033
03:34:10,304 --> 03:34:13,068
I was, I was at the mercy
of the safety divers.

5034
03:34:13,307 --> 03:34:14,296
If I needed air, I would signal,
give a hand signal.

5035
03:34:14,541 --> 03:34:17,169
The divers would swim in.

5036
03:34:17,411 --> 03:34:19,538
They'd lift my mask and put
a regulator right in my mouth.

5037
03:34:19,980 --> 03:34:21,971
All of the above-the-water
scenes

5038
03:34:22,216 --> 03:34:26,915
were shot in this murky,
eerie lake

5039
03:34:27,154 --> 03:34:29,213
in the middle-of-nowhere
Georgia,

5040
03:34:29,456 --> 03:34:30,582
in the middle of the night.

5041
03:34:31,024 --> 03:34:33,925
So, that was terrible.

5042
03:34:34,161 --> 03:34:36,425
I believe we shot
in Tom McLoughlin's

5043
03:34:36,864 --> 03:34:38,832
father's swimming pool
after the fact,

5044
03:34:39,066 --> 03:34:41,864
of the motor,
the blade from the motor,

5045
03:34:42,102 --> 03:34:44,036
cutting Jason's mask,
and the blood coming out.

5046
03:34:44,271 --> 03:34:48,332
Jason has, you know,
obviously lived

5047
03:34:48,575 --> 03:34:50,839
far beyond
anybody's expectations

5048
03:34:51,078 --> 03:34:51,908
because even when l
was doing the film,

5049
03:34:52,145 --> 03:34:54,113
it was pretty much,

5050
03:34:54,348 --> 03:34:55,440
"Well, I think this is probably
going to be the last one,

5051
03:34:55,883 --> 03:34:58,215
and so just have fun with him,

5052
03:34:58,452 --> 03:34:59,942
but don't kill him kill him"

5053
03:35:00,187 --> 03:35:00,983
which is why I had him,
you know,

5054
03:35:01,221 --> 03:35:02,347
hanging there in the bottom.

5055
03:35:02,589 --> 03:35:03,283
I mean, you can see
at the end of the movie,

5056
03:35:03,523 --> 03:35:04,615
the eye opens up,

5057
03:35:05,058 --> 03:35:07,253
and the man behind the mask
is still alive,

5058
03:35:07,494 --> 03:35:09,052
and it just sets it up
for the next phase.

5059
03:35:09,296 --> 03:35:11,127
As with all
of the previous "Fridays,"

5060
03:35:11,365 --> 03:35:13,094
a number of different endings
were suggested,

5061
03:35:13,333 --> 03:35:16,268
though none were ever
quite so daring

5062
03:35:16,503 --> 03:35:18,266
as Tom McLoughlin's scripted
though never filmed

5063
03:35:18,505 --> 03:35:20,439
cliffhanger.

5064
03:35:20,674 --> 03:35:22,608
Tom McLoughlin had written
a different ending

5065
03:35:23,043 --> 03:35:25,910
where you met Jason's father.

5066
03:35:26,146 --> 03:35:28,114
We'd seen Jason's mother.

5067
03:35:28,348 --> 03:35:29,975
We understand how messed up
Pamela is.

5068
03:35:30,217 --> 03:35:32,117
Well, who marries that woman?.

5069
03:35:32,352 --> 03:35:34,377
And, really, what did he
have to do with this ultimately?.

5070
03:35:34,621 --> 03:35:36,316
We don't know who he was,
what he was, or anything.

5071
03:35:36,556 --> 03:35:38,490
So I thought it would be

5072
03:35:38,926 --> 03:35:41,486
really interesting
at the end of mine to, you know,

5073
03:35:41,929 --> 03:35:43,487
have him show up.

5074
03:35:43,931 --> 03:35:46,957
In my original script,
the caretaker had not died.

5075
03:35:47,200 --> 03:35:48,929
He was still around.

5076
03:35:49,169 --> 03:35:52,036
So he was, you know,
it had a kind of an epilogue

5077
03:35:52,272 --> 03:35:56,140
with him in the cemetery
and in walks this guy,

5078
03:35:56,376 --> 03:35:59,345
kind of an almost Rasputin,
you know,

5079
03:35:59,579 --> 03:36:01,069
type character you didn't
get to see too much of,

5080
03:36:01,315 --> 03:36:03,977
and you realize
that he's the one

5081
03:36:04,217 --> 03:36:06,344
who's been paying the caretaker

5082
03:36:06,586 --> 03:36:09,054
to take care of Jason's grave
all these years.

5083
03:36:09,289 --> 03:36:10,221
And you now kind of understand
that whatever Jason came from,

5084
03:36:10,457 --> 03:36:14,484
you know, the truly wicked side
of him,

5085
03:36:14,728 --> 03:36:16,923
was his father.

5086
03:36:17,164 --> 03:36:20,565
What I got worried about with
Tom's idea about Jason's father

5087
03:36:21,001 --> 03:36:22,332
is that if you sort of dangle
like something like that

5088
03:36:22,569 --> 03:36:24,503
at the end of the movie,

5089
03:36:24,738 --> 03:36:26,569
all of a sudden
we're trying to tell the story

5090
03:36:27,007 --> 03:36:28,531
of a 60-year-old guy,

5091
03:36:28,976 --> 03:36:31,001
and how that would sort of
circle back around

5092
03:36:31,244 --> 03:36:33,508
into a movie that we could
actually sort of make work.

5093
03:36:33,747 --> 03:36:36,079
Frank Mancuso felt that, no,

5094
03:36:36,316 --> 03:36:38,079
we don't want to split,
you know,

5095
03:36:38,318 --> 03:36:40,309
the attention of the franchise
off on something like that

5096
03:36:40,554 --> 03:36:42,385
as cool as it, you know,
the idea might be.

5097
03:36:42,622 --> 03:36:44,522
You know, stay with Jason

5098
03:36:44,758 --> 03:36:46,089
and probably
he's ultimately right.

5099
03:36:46,326 --> 03:36:48,021
The Elias Voorhees character
I think

5100
03:36:48,261 --> 03:36:49,250
really would have been
very interesting to visit.

5101
03:36:49,496 --> 03:36:51,054
That I think was a bit
of a missed opportunity.

5102
03:36:51,298 --> 03:36:53,095
Maybe the people
who didn't like "Part 7"

5103
03:36:53,333 --> 03:36:56,530
would have thought that would
have been a better movie.

5104
03:36:56,770 --> 03:36:58,101
I don't know. But I was happy
that they actually released

5105
03:36:58,338 --> 03:37:01,068
a Signet Pocketbook version
of the movie,

5106
03:37:01,308 --> 03:37:04,368
which has, you know, that aspect
in it at the end of it.

5107
03:37:04,611 --> 03:37:06,704
In a further attempt
to broaden the film's appeal,

5108
03:37:07,147 --> 03:37:09,581
Paramount recruited legendary
shock rocker Alice Cooper

5109
03:37:10,017 --> 03:37:12,042
to contribute
three songs to the film.

5110
03:37:12,285 --> 03:37:14,344
You don't have to be a genius
to take a look at me

5111
03:37:14,588 --> 03:37:17,056
and realize I'm an old rocker
that refuses to die

5112
03:37:17,290 --> 03:37:20,487
and so when, all the movies
I always try to put

5113
03:37:20,727 --> 03:37:22,388
as much rock music in as I can.

5114
03:37:22,629 --> 03:37:25,120
The music score
done by Alice Cooper

5115
03:37:25,365 --> 03:37:27,356
was done after the fact,
but it was a very cool thing.

5116
03:37:27,601 --> 03:37:29,728
We didn't mind
a little blood on stage,

5117
03:37:30,170 --> 03:37:32,161
and a little, you know,
slash here and there.

5118
03:37:32,406 --> 03:37:36,342
And so when the slasher movies
came along in the '80s,

5119
03:37:36,576 --> 03:37:39,602
all of a sudden
we were right there.

5120
03:37:40,047 --> 03:37:42,277
So when it came to writing
for Jason, you know,

5121
03:37:42,516 --> 03:37:44,108
Jason's like a member
of the band.

5122
03:37:44,351 --> 03:37:46,046
They came to us and they said,

5123
03:37:46,286 --> 03:37:48,254
could you write 2 or 3 songs
for the movie,

5124
03:37:48,488 --> 03:37:50,285
a couple of incidentals
and a theme.

5125
03:37:50,524 --> 03:37:51,786
And I went, "Yeah, absolutely."

5126
03:37:52,225 --> 03:37:54,455
Alice was incredible

5127
03:37:54,694 --> 03:37:56,685
to just kind of let us use
whatever songs we wanted.

5128
03:37:57,130 --> 03:37:59,155
And the song that he came up
with was just huge.

5129
03:37:59,399 --> 03:38:02,300
Yeah cuz he's back

5130
03:38:02,536 --> 03:38:05,699
He's the man behind the mask

5131
03:38:06,139 --> 03:38:08,539
And he's out of control

5132
03:38:08,775 --> 03:38:10,675
"The Man Behind the Mask" was
written 3 or 4 different ways.

5133
03:38:11,111 --> 03:38:14,080
We wrote a heavy metal version
of it.

5134
03:38:14,314 --> 03:38:17,579
And then we wrote sort of
a hard rock version.

5135
03:38:17,818 --> 03:38:20,116
and then we realized
at that time

5136
03:38:20,353 --> 03:38:21,342
that they were looking
for something

5137
03:38:21,588 --> 03:38:23,579
a little more...

5138
03:38:23,824 --> 03:38:26,520
a little more bounce to it.

5139
03:38:26,760 --> 03:38:28,387
And so we got together
with Kelly

5140
03:38:28,628 --> 03:38:34,089
who wrote, I think
"Material Girl" for Madonna,

5141
03:38:34,334 --> 03:38:37,167
and he was the one that came in
with that [hums bass]

5142
03:38:37,404 --> 03:38:39,736
Early test screenings
of "Jason Lives"

5143
03:38:40,173 --> 03:38:42,539
did not fully satisfy
Paramount executives.

5144
03:38:42,776 --> 03:38:44,835
so they decided to enhance
the film's thrill quotient

5145
03:38:45,278 --> 03:38:47,303
by increasing its body count.

5146
03:38:47,547 --> 03:38:50,448
And I do remember
being in meetings

5147
03:38:50,684 --> 03:38:53,244
talking about who can we kill,
how will they get killed.

5148
03:38:53,487 --> 03:38:55,182
And that's where I came in.

5149
03:38:55,422 --> 03:38:58,289
Oh Steven, it's beautiful.

5150
03:38:58,525 --> 03:39:00,789
I am friends with
Tom McLoughlin, the director.

5151
03:39:01,228 --> 03:39:04,391
So I knew him beforehand.

5152
03:39:04,631 --> 03:39:05,563
He had directed my husband
Vinnie Guasterferro,

5153
03:39:05,799 --> 03:39:08,131
who is the deputy,

5154
03:39:08,368 --> 03:39:11,860
and so he hired me to shoot
the scene we did.

5155
03:39:12,305 --> 03:39:14,205
We shot that at Griffith Park
here in LA.

5156
03:39:14,441 --> 03:39:16,841
And he shish-ke-bobs them

5157
03:39:17,277 --> 03:39:17,800
where it puts it
right through the front

5158
03:39:18,245 --> 03:39:19,610
and right through the back.

5159
03:39:19,846 --> 03:39:22,212
I know we weren't the first
shish-ke-bob

5160
03:39:22,449 --> 03:39:24,349
to occur
in "Friday the 1 3th"

5161
03:39:24,584 --> 03:39:28,486
but I think we were the first
on a motor scooter.

5162
03:39:28,722 --> 03:39:30,314
That is probably
our claim to fame.

5163
03:39:30,557 --> 03:39:31,615
Optimistic about
the film's chances

5164
03:39:31,858 --> 03:39:33,826
of playing to a summer audience,

5165
03:39:34,261 --> 03:39:36,729
Paramount Pictures bumped up
its release date

5166
03:39:37,164 --> 03:39:38,825
to August 1, 1 986.

5167
03:39:39,266 --> 03:39:41,791
Despite being the only
"Friday the 1 3th"

5168
03:39:42,235 --> 03:39:44,601
to receive the occasional
positive notice,

5169
03:39:44,838 --> 03:39:48,501
the film failed to capture
the #1 spot at the box office,

5170
03:39:48,742 --> 03:39:50,539
falling behind another
high-profile horror sequel,

5171
03:39:50,777 --> 03:39:52,768
James Cameron's "Aliens."

5172
03:39:53,213 --> 03:39:57,240
With a final tally
of $19.5 million

5173
03:39:57,484 --> 03:39:59,816
"Jason Lives" became
the lowest-grossing

5174
03:40:00,253 --> 03:40:02,244
"Friday the 1 3th" to date.

5175
03:40:02,489 --> 03:40:04,821
And I really think the reason 6
didn't do well

5176
03:40:05,258 --> 03:40:08,716
is not because 6 is not as good,
if not better,

5177
03:40:08,962 --> 03:40:10,589
but the fans
didn't really come back

5178
03:40:10,830 --> 03:40:13,264
because they felt so ripped off
by 5.

5179
03:40:13,500 --> 03:40:17,630
And then when they began
to see 6 on video,

5180
03:40:17,871 --> 03:40:21,204
that got them back
into the series

5181
03:40:21,441 --> 03:40:23,636
because they saw that Tom
McLoughlin, more than anybody,

5182
03:40:23,877 --> 03:40:25,811
brought the series back to life.

5183
03:40:26,246 --> 03:40:28,578
I was really happy with
the movie, the way it came out.

5184
03:40:28,815 --> 03:40:30,544
I'm still happy with it. I think
it holds up really well.

5185
03:40:30,784 --> 03:40:32,547
And I sure had fun filming it.

5186
03:40:32,786 --> 03:40:34,583
I never got to go to summer camp

5187
03:40:34,821 --> 03:40:37,381
so it was the closest
I ever got.

5188
03:40:37,624 --> 03:40:39,785
And I thought Tom did
a really good job on that movie.

5189
03:40:40,227 --> 03:40:41,387
I thought that he brought
a lightness to it,

5190
03:40:41,628 --> 03:40:42,492
a fun-ness to it.

5191
03:40:42,729 --> 03:40:44,321
He had a great sensibility.

5192
03:40:44,564 --> 03:40:47,226
He had a real appreciation
of the movies.

5193
03:40:47,467 --> 03:40:49,526
And as a result, we had a lot
of very good reviews on the film

5194
03:40:49,769 --> 03:40:50,929
because they said,

5195
03:40:51,371 --> 03:40:52,463
"Well, you can't really
hate a movie

5196
03:40:52,706 --> 03:40:52,899
that is making fun of itself."

5197
03:40:53,340 --> 03:40:55,467
Yet, you know,
for most of the fans,

5198
03:40:55,709 --> 03:41:03,750
it still delivered, you know,
what a "Friday" should deliver.

5199
03:41:03,750 --> 03:41:15,526
it still delivered, you know,
what a "Friday" should deliver.

5200
03:41:15,762 --> 03:41:18,253
By the late 1 980s, Paramount
was looking for new ways

5201
03:41:18,498 --> 03:41:20,295
to exploit their most lucrative
franchises.

5202
03:41:20,533 --> 03:41:22,558
To the dismay of its critics,

5203
03:41:22,802 --> 03:41:25,293
"Friday the 1 3th"
would soon be coming

5204
03:41:25,538 --> 03:41:27,438
to television.

5205
03:41:27,674 --> 03:41:29,767
Mel Harris, who was at the time
head of Paramount Television,

5206
03:41:30,010 --> 03:41:32,877
came to me and he said,

5207
03:41:33,313 --> 03:41:35,406
you know, "We're having a very
successful syndication run

5208
03:41:35,649 --> 03:41:36,843
with "Star Trek."

5209
03:41:37,284 --> 03:41:39,616
We want to try to identify
some other titles

5210
03:41:39,853 --> 03:41:42,583
that we control that we think
will bring an audience.

5211
03:41:42,822 --> 03:41:44,949
Just by virtue of the title."

5212
03:41:45,392 --> 03:41:49,294
It was essential that we found
a way to tell stories

5213
03:41:49,529 --> 03:41:52,896
that would have a kind of
"Friday the 1 3th" theme

5214
03:41:53,333 --> 03:41:53,822
without being directly
associated

5215
03:41:54,067 --> 03:41:56,399
with "Friday the 1 3th."

5216
03:41:56,636 --> 03:41:57,864
And he said, "Look, this has
nothing to do with the movies.

5217
03:41:58,305 --> 03:41:59,363
It could be anything
that you want.

5218
03:41:59,606 --> 03:42:00,732
It just has to be
"Friday the 1 3th,"

5219
03:42:00,974 --> 03:42:02,373
and you have to be involved."

5220
03:42:02,609 --> 03:42:04,304
I remember when I was a kid
going--

5221
03:42:04,544 --> 03:42:05,772
doing like the 11 :00
monster movies, and it's like,

5222
03:42:06,012 --> 03:42:07,741
you know,
kind of freaks you out

5223
03:42:07,981 --> 03:42:09,039
and then you gotta go to sleep.

5224
03:42:09,482 --> 03:42:11,541
What I need
is a Vampira cocktail

5225
03:42:11,785 --> 03:42:13,878
to settle my nerves.

5226
03:42:14,321 --> 03:42:15,379
It will not only settle them,

5227
03:42:15,622 --> 03:42:18,785
it will petrify them.

5228
03:42:19,025 --> 03:42:22,051
And that's kind of the dynamic
that I was looking for.

5229
03:42:22,495 --> 03:42:24,486
With only a title to work with,

5230
03:42:24,731 --> 03:42:26,699
Mancuso and co-creator
Larry B. Williams

5231
03:42:26,933 --> 03:42:28,867
began brainstorming a premise

5232
03:42:29,102 --> 03:42:31,366
that could sustain itself
in the world

5233
03:42:31,604 --> 03:42:32,730
of late-night
syndicated television.

5234
03:42:32,972 --> 03:42:35,566
Like the films themselves,

5235
03:42:35,809 --> 03:42:38,369
"Friday the 1 3th: The Series"
had to be made cheap.

5236
03:42:38,611 --> 03:42:41,341
And it had to be scary.

5237
03:42:41,581 --> 03:42:44,948
And I was kind of intent
on doing an anthology

5238
03:42:45,385 --> 03:42:46,943
with continuing characters,

5239
03:42:47,387 --> 03:42:49,685
so we started talking about
the notion of a curio shop

5240
03:42:49,923 --> 03:42:51,686
and what that would be like.

5241
03:42:51,925 --> 03:42:53,324
And then the idea
of it being cursed

5242
03:42:53,560 --> 03:42:54,891
and then we started saying,
"Well, you know,

5243
03:42:55,128 --> 03:42:56,425
if we had all these
cursed objects,

5244
03:42:56,663 --> 03:42:59,598
then we can go ahead and have
a great time with that."

5245
03:42:59,833 --> 03:43:03,098
So that really became the sort
of the core of the show.

5246
03:43:03,536 --> 03:43:07,097
Frank's plan with "The Series"

5247
03:43:07,540 --> 03:43:09,667
is that all these antiques
were cursed,

5248
03:43:09,909 --> 03:43:11,706
but they all could actually
service you

5249
03:43:11,945 --> 03:43:13,469
in something really good,

5250
03:43:13,713 --> 03:43:15,681
but there's always
a price to pay.

5251
03:43:15,915 --> 03:43:18,941
The allure of the object
that is cursed

5252
03:43:19,386 --> 03:43:21,547
and the things that happen
to people

5253
03:43:21,788 --> 03:43:22,777
with that object
in their possession

5254
03:43:23,022 --> 03:43:24,649
is really a terrific idea.

5255
03:43:24,891 --> 03:43:27,382
And it was a terrific
launching pad

5256
03:43:27,627 --> 03:43:29,891
for really some--some really
fascinating storytelling.

5257
03:43:30,130 --> 03:43:32,758
Lewis Vendredi
made a deal with the devil

5258
03:43:32,999 --> 03:43:35,968
to sell cursed antiques.

5259
03:43:36,403 --> 03:43:40,464
But he broke the pact,
and it cost him his soul...

5260
03:43:40,707 --> 03:43:43,107
Distributed by Paramount
Domestic Syndication,

5261
03:43:43,543 --> 03:43:47,980
"Friday the 1 3th: The Series"
debuted on September 28, 1987.

5262
03:43:48,415 --> 03:43:52,511
It told the story of cousins
Ryan Dallion and Micki Foster

5263
03:43:52,752 --> 03:43:54,777
who inherit an antique store
from a distant uncle

5264
03:43:55,021 --> 03:43:57,012
who sold his soul to the devil.

5265
03:43:57,457 --> 03:44:00,119
Aided by antiquities expert
Jack Marshak,

5266
03:44:00,560 --> 03:44:03,085
their quest was to retrieve
the cursed objects

5267
03:44:03,530 --> 03:44:09,435
before obsession and death
came to those who acquired them.

5268
03:44:09,669 --> 03:44:11,728
I'd been out in Los Angeles
for three years

5269
03:44:11,971 --> 03:44:14,963
and got an audition
for this television series.

5270
03:44:15,208 --> 03:44:16,869
It all just happened very fast.

5271
03:44:17,110 --> 03:44:19,169
Went in for a wardrobe fitting
and was on a plane to Toronto.

5272
03:44:19,612 --> 03:44:22,445
Robey, John LeMay and
Chris Wiggins were a dream cast.

5273
03:44:22,682 --> 03:44:27,016
Chris is a senior emeritus
honored Canadian actor,

5274
03:44:27,454 --> 03:44:30,014
and it surprised us when we
asked him to join the cast

5275
03:44:30,457 --> 03:44:31,651
and he said yes.

5276
03:44:31,891 --> 03:44:33,756
So they wanted to shoot like

5277
03:44:33,993 --> 03:44:34,982
this little pilot kind of thing,
which I directed,

5278
03:44:35,228 --> 03:44:36,627
and, you know,
it was very contained,

5279
03:44:36,863 --> 03:44:38,990
very small, and, you know, we
probably did it for $85.

5280
03:44:39,232 --> 03:44:41,166
I have no time for you!

5281
03:44:41,601 --> 03:44:43,796
But it communicated what we
were meant to communicate

5282
03:44:44,037 --> 03:44:45,004
which is that, you know,

5283
03:44:45,238 --> 03:44:45,567
it's going to be scary,
it's going to be spooky,

5284
03:44:45,805 --> 03:44:46,965
it's going to be tense.

5285
03:44:47,207 --> 03:44:48,606
With not a single episode

5286
03:44:48,842 --> 03:44:50,503
featuring an appearance
by Jason,

5287
03:44:50,743 --> 03:44:53,041
or even his cursed hockey mask,

5288
03:44:53,480 --> 03:44:56,745
many "Friday the 1 3th" fans
felt alienated.

5289
03:44:56,983 --> 03:44:59,975
And even cheated by its
television counterpart.

5290
03:45:00,220 --> 03:45:02,586
The only thing
that the television series

5291
03:45:02,822 --> 03:45:07,555
"Friday the 1 3th" and the movies
"Friday the 1 3th" had in common

5292
03:45:07,794 --> 03:45:10,763
was the title
and Frank Mancuso, Jr.

5293
03:45:10,997 --> 03:45:13,090
While "Friday the 1 3th"
as a title was a come-on,

5294
03:45:13,533 --> 03:45:14,625
we really felt that there
was something there.

5295
03:45:14,868 --> 03:45:16,802
There is no concept

5296
03:45:17,036 --> 03:45:18,128
that could have sustained itself
on television

5297
03:45:18,571 --> 03:45:21,631
with a slasher killer
on the loose

5298
03:45:21,875 --> 03:45:26,710
anywhere for the 76 episodes
that were subsequently made.

5299
03:45:26,946 --> 03:45:28,174
I really wish they would have
called it "Friday's Curse."

5300
03:45:28,615 --> 03:45:31,209
Which was the original
intention.

5301
03:45:31,651 --> 03:45:33,710
In Europe it was called
"Friday's Curse,"

5302
03:45:33,953 --> 03:45:36,513
and in Canada it was called
"Friday's Curse" as well.

5303
03:45:36,756 --> 03:45:39,486
It was set up in Canada
and I was producing the show.

5304
03:45:39,726 --> 03:45:42,854
And it was
a fascinating experience.

5305
03:45:43,096 --> 03:45:44,996
And we got like Atom Egoyan
to do one.

5306
03:45:45,231 --> 03:45:47,096
David Cronenberg did one.

5307
03:45:47,534 --> 03:45:49,126
David Cronenberg brought that
terrific kind of

5308
03:45:49,569 --> 03:45:52,060
Iaser-like focus on a theme

5309
03:45:52,305 --> 03:45:54,671
which so totally fit into
the storytelling notions

5310
03:45:54,908 --> 03:45:55,840
of "Friday the 1 3th."

5311
03:45:56,075 --> 03:45:58,009
And it was wonderful.

5312
03:45:58,244 --> 03:45:59,575
It was also great
to work with David

5313
03:45:59,812 --> 03:46:01,643
who's a fabulous director.

5314
03:46:01,881 --> 03:46:04,543
Frank asked me about being
story editor

5315
03:46:04,784 --> 03:46:06,752
because they had a story editor
up in Toronto

5316
03:46:06,986 --> 03:46:10,149
where they were doing the show,
and, you know,

5317
03:46:10,590 --> 03:46:12,023
wanted me to write and direct,
you know,

5318
03:46:12,258 --> 03:46:13,885
some episodes as well.

5319
03:46:14,127 --> 03:46:16,618
"Master of Disguise,"
I thought was a great idea

5320
03:46:16,863 --> 03:46:19,730
basically having, you know,
a makeup case that, you know,

5321
03:46:19,966 --> 03:46:21,058
could take somebody who was
really deformed

5322
03:46:21,301 --> 03:46:23,565
and, you know, you'd kill

5323
03:46:23,803 --> 03:46:26,863
and then you would sop up
the blood of the victim

5324
03:46:27,106 --> 03:46:29,006
and then he was as handsome
as like a James Bond.

5325
03:46:29,242 --> 03:46:31,870
And because it was syndication,

5326
03:46:32,111 --> 03:46:36,639
we literally never got a note
from anybody about anything.

5327
03:46:36,883 --> 03:46:37,645
I mean, I don't know that
anybody

5328
03:46:37,884 --> 03:46:39,647
even looked at the shows.

5329
03:46:39,886 --> 03:46:41,080
I mean, it was like literally
they just went out.

5330
03:46:41,321 --> 03:46:42,083
So if I wanted to do it
in black and white,

5331
03:46:42,322 --> 03:46:44,017
it was black and white.

5332
03:46:44,257 --> 03:46:46,191
If I wanted to do a two-parter,
you did a two-parter.

5333
03:46:46,626 --> 03:46:47,923
I mean, it was like literally
whatever we decided to do.

5334
03:46:48,161 --> 03:46:50,857
"Friday the 1 3th,"
the new television series

5335
03:46:51,097 --> 03:46:54,555
that has put real fright
into late night.

5336
03:46:54,801 --> 03:46:58,066
"Friday The 1 3th: The Series"
was a bona fide ratings hit.

5337
03:46:58,304 --> 03:47:00,738
Often ranking just behind
Paramount's

5338
03:47:00,974 --> 03:47:03,101
top-rated "Star Trek:
The Next Generation."

5339
03:47:03,343 --> 03:47:04,935
After two successful seasons,

5340
03:47:05,178 --> 03:47:07,305
actor John LeMay
decided to leave the show

5341
03:47:07,747 --> 03:47:09,977
to pursue other opportunities.

5342
03:47:10,216 --> 03:47:11,979
The thing that was the most
interesting of a challenge

5343
03:47:12,218 --> 03:47:14,209
was the third season,

5344
03:47:14,654 --> 03:47:16,815
Frank asked me if I would
write and direct

5345
03:47:17,056 --> 03:47:18,956
for the season premiere.

5346
03:47:19,192 --> 03:47:21,285
And he said, "You know, we need
to kill the Ryan character

5347
03:47:21,728 --> 03:47:22,990
because he wants to get off
the show,

5348
03:47:23,229 --> 03:47:26,062
and but don't kill him
in a way

5349
03:47:26,299 --> 03:47:28,199
that we can't bring him back
if he changes his mind.

5350
03:47:28,635 --> 03:47:30,000
And I got turned back
into a child

5351
03:47:30,236 --> 03:47:32,932
at the end of my two-year stint
on the show.

5352
03:47:33,172 --> 03:47:36,164
It was a grand and glorious
two hour episode.

5353
03:47:36,409 --> 03:47:39,674
It was a way of basically
taking him off the show

5354
03:47:39,912 --> 03:47:42,176
and, if you wanted
to bring him back, you could.

5355
03:47:42,415 --> 03:47:43,643
When LeMay was replaced in
the third season opener

5356
03:47:43,883 --> 03:47:45,009
by actor Steven Monarque

5357
03:47:45,251 --> 03:47:47,310
as streetwise Johnny Ventura

5358
03:47:47,754 --> 03:47:49,119
"The Series" lost not only
its leading man,

5359
03:47:49,355 --> 03:47:51,220
but its luster.

5360
03:47:51,658 --> 03:47:53,683
Once Ryan got turned into
a little boy,

5361
03:47:53,926 --> 03:47:56,360
Johnny Ventura had to take over
that spot.

5362
03:47:56,796 --> 03:47:57,956
Johnny...

5363
03:47:58,197 --> 03:48:00,392
Johnny was the cousin of Ryan.

5364
03:48:00,833 --> 03:48:03,199
He was a little bit more
of a blue-collar kid.

5365
03:48:03,436 --> 03:48:06,701
I don't think he was afraid
of fighting

5366
03:48:06,939 --> 03:48:08,873
and physically getting involved
with saving the day.

5367
03:48:09,108 --> 03:48:11,269
[monster growling sounds]

5368
03:48:11,711 --> 03:48:13,269
"Friday the 1 3th"
and "Nightmare on Elm Street"

5369
03:48:13,713 --> 03:48:15,874
were head-to-head in terms
of their television experience.

5370
03:48:16,115 --> 03:48:18,743
"Freddy's Nightmares" was always
a somewhat more lighthearted,

5371
03:48:18,985 --> 03:48:20,748
tongue-in-cheek
kind of a television series.

5372
03:48:20,987 --> 03:48:22,921
I think the makers
of "Friday the 1 3th"

5373
03:48:23,156 --> 03:48:24,214
always wanted it to be dark,

5374
03:48:24,457 --> 03:48:25,947
always wanted it
serious quality.

5375
03:48:26,192 --> 03:48:27,250
Because the show
got good reviews,

5376
03:48:27,694 --> 03:48:29,059
and the show was successful,

5377
03:48:29,295 --> 03:48:30,887
the people at Paramount said,

5378
03:48:31,130 --> 03:48:34,861
"lf we can get X dollars
at 1 1 :00,

5379
03:48:35,101 --> 03:48:36,864
if we move it to 1 0:00
we can even get more."

5380
03:48:37,103 --> 03:48:39,901
So they moved it to 1 0:00
in year two.

5381
03:48:40,139 --> 03:48:41,800
And all of a sudden it's like
even more successful.

5382
03:48:42,041 --> 03:48:43,668
They said, "You know what?.

5383
03:48:43,910 --> 03:48:45,002
Let's start putting it on
at 7:00, 8:00, you know,

5384
03:48:45,244 --> 03:48:46,233
whatever it is.

5385
03:48:46,479 --> 03:48:47,343
They start moving it.

5386
03:48:47,780 --> 03:48:49,805
So now, all of a sudden,

5387
03:48:50,049 --> 03:48:51,107
different kinds of people
are watching.

5388
03:48:51,350 --> 03:48:52,374
No longer is it
the last thing that you see

5389
03:48:52,819 --> 03:48:54,309
before you go to bed at night.

5390
03:48:54,754 --> 03:48:56,244
Now it's like, it's on at 7:00.

5391
03:48:56,489 --> 03:48:58,150
They stopped the clock, Lewis!

5392
03:48:58,391 --> 03:49:00,222
[screams]

5393
03:49:00,460 --> 03:49:03,020
Here you are,
sitting at home, eating dinner

5394
03:49:03,262 --> 03:49:04,752
and all of a sudden this,
you know,

5395
03:49:04,997 --> 03:49:06,328
splat thriller
comes on the tube.

5396
03:49:06,766 --> 03:49:08,700
I think, you know, as a parent

5397
03:49:08,935 --> 03:49:10,869
it would catch me
by surprise, too.

5398
03:49:11,104 --> 03:49:13,038
And with Paramount
boldly pushing the show

5399
03:49:13,272 --> 03:49:16,241
into primetime slots,
"Friday the 13th: The Series"

5400
03:49:16,476 --> 03:49:18,444
soon came under fire from
right-wing religious groups

5401
03:49:18,878 --> 03:49:20,812
who were less than enthused
about a show

5402
03:49:21,047 --> 03:49:23,106
involving black magic
and pacts with the devil.

5403
03:49:23,349 --> 03:49:25,476
I think when I came in
at the time,

5404
03:49:25,918 --> 03:49:28,216
people were already
not liking he show.

5405
03:49:28,454 --> 03:49:30,081
There was already this force
trying to get it off the air.

5406
03:49:30,323 --> 03:49:33,815
So this guy, Donald Wildmon,

5407
03:49:34,060 --> 03:49:36,028
who had like this kind of
Christian Coalition group

5408
03:49:36,262 --> 03:49:39,356
started squawking about
"Friday the 1 3th"

5409
03:49:39,799 --> 03:49:40,390
because it started
to get recognized.

5410
03:49:40,833 --> 03:49:42,164
He's talking about Jason.

5411
03:49:42,401 --> 03:49:44,460
He's talking about,
you know, all this stuff.

5412
03:49:44,904 --> 03:49:45,393
I'm saying, this guy's never
even seen one of the shows.

5413
03:49:45,838 --> 03:49:47,271
What's at stake here?.

5414
03:49:47,507 --> 03:49:49,975
Western civilization
as we've known it

5415
03:49:50,209 --> 03:49:52,268
for two thousand years.

5416
03:49:52,512 --> 03:49:54,742
We kind of all laughed him off
in the beginning.

5417
03:49:54,981 --> 03:49:56,346
But, you know, you get somebody
like that who calls and says,

5418
03:49:56,783 --> 03:49:59,513
"Yeah, I got 555,000
constituents,

5419
03:49:59,952 --> 03:50:01,749
and they're not going to buy
Proctor & Gamble products

5420
03:50:01,988 --> 03:50:04,354
if you continue to put your ads
on this show."

5421
03:50:04,791 --> 03:50:06,122
All of a sudden
it's not so funny anymore.

5422
03:50:06,359 --> 03:50:08,827
I was sad that it ended
that quickly.

5423
03:50:09,061 --> 03:50:11,757
You know I really wanted to do
at least another year or two

5424
03:50:11,998 --> 03:50:14,296
because I was just finally
getting my feet wet.

5425
03:50:14,534 --> 03:50:17,469
It's amazing how our culture
has changed in 20 years

5426
03:50:17,904 --> 03:50:19,804
and how permissive and pervasive
violence, in particular,

5427
03:50:20,039 --> 03:50:22,007
is on TV,

5428
03:50:22,241 --> 03:50:23,970
and how much it's just
taken for granted,

5429
03:50:24,210 --> 03:50:26,075
that it's just
going to be there.

5430
03:50:26,312 --> 03:50:28,473
So, yeah, it was sad because
we did, what, 73 hours

5431
03:50:28,915 --> 03:50:31,145
and, you know,
there were some clunkers,

5432
03:50:31,384 --> 03:50:32,373
but there were a lot
of really good shows in there.

5433
03:50:32,819 --> 03:50:35,253
And, in point of fact,

5434
03:50:35,488 --> 03:50:36,819
when I talk to people
about the television series,

5435
03:50:37,056 --> 03:50:38,785
you know, people do
remember it fondly.

5436
03:50:39,025 --> 03:50:40,492
But I think a lot of people

5437
03:50:40,927 --> 03:50:42,485
who were really big fans
of the series

5438
03:50:42,929 --> 03:50:45,227
didn't like the fact
that they stole the name

5439
03:50:45,464 --> 03:50:49,059
and tried to sneak a fast one
past everybody

5440
03:50:49,302 --> 03:50:52,396
and get them to watch
this hour serial on TV.

5441
03:50:52,839 --> 03:50:55,239
But it was fun. I liked it.